 on the appropriate levels of potassium and fluid intake, and advised to seek medical attention if they experience signs and symptoms of hyperkalemia such as nausea, vomiting, weakness, listlessness, tingling of the extremities, paralysis, confusion, weak pulse, and a slow or irregular heartbeat.', 'Synergism', 'Calcium chloride, Zinc sulfate, Magnesium sulfate, Sodium acetate, Arginine, Sodium glycerophosphate, Zinc chloride, Tromethamine, Sodium bicarbonate, Sodium chloride, Ammonium chloride, Magnesium chloride', 'Sacubitril, Nebivolol', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/178275/', '[1] Walmsley RN, White GH, Cain M, McCarthy PJ, Booth J "Hyperkalemia in the elderly." Clin Chem 30 (1984): 1409-12[2] Jarman PR, Mather HM "Diabetes may be independent risk factor for hyperkalaemia." BMJ 327 (2003): 812[3] Obialo CI, Ofili EO, Mirza T "Hyperkalemia in congestive heart failure patients aged 63 to 85 years with subclinical renal disease." Am J Cardiol 90 (2002): 663-5[4] Jarman PR, Kehely AM, Mather HM "Hyperkalaemia in diabetes: prevalence and associations." Postgrad Med J 71 (1995): 551-2[5] "Product Information. Cozaar (losartan)." Merck & Co, Inc, West Point, PA.[6] Large DM, Carr PH, Laing I, Davies M "Hyperkalaemia in diabetes mellitus--potential hazards of coexisting hyporeninaemic hypoaldosteronism." Postgrad Med J 60 (1984): 370-3[7] Perazella MA "Drug-induced hyperkalemia: old culprits and new offenders." Am J Med 109 (2000): 307-14[8] "Product Information. Diovan (valsartan)." Novartis Pharmaceuticals, East Hanover, NJ.[9] Perazella MA, Mahnensmith RL "Hyperkalemia in the elderly: drugs exacerbate impaired potassium homeostasis." J Gen Intern Med 12 (1997): 646-56[10] Lawson DH "Adverse reactions to potassium chloride." Q J Med 43 (1974): 433-40[11] Lawson DH, O''Connor PC, Jick H "Drug attributed alterations in potassium handling in congestive cardiac failure." Eur J Clin Pharmacol 23 (1982): 21-5[